title: For Sale:  BUFFALO BORE AMMO - .45 ACP +P AMMO - 230 GR. J.H.P. (950 FPS/M.E. 461 FT. LBS.) - 50 ROUND BOX
postcontent:
http://extreme-impact-ammo.com/index.php?l=product_detail&p=68

45ACP+P ammo is externally/dimensionally identical to 45 ACP ammo and can be fired in any 45 acp firearm that is in normal operating condition. However, the greater pressures and power of the +P ammo will give you greater slide velocity and if you are going to shoot more than a box or two of +P ammo, you should consider replacing your recoil spring with a Wolf Spring that gives roughly 4 to 6 lbs more spring weight than factory stock springs. A shock buffer might also be a good addition although it is not too necessary if you use the stronger spring.


The below velocities were fired from my personal Colt Gold Cup 1911 (5 inch)


1. 45185-----------1180 fps (185gr. Jhp)
2. 45200-----------1078 fps (200gr. Jhp)
3. 45230------------979 fps (230gr. Jhp)
4. 45230FMJ------981 fps (230gr. Fmj-FLAT NOSE)
5. 45255------------960 fps (255gr. HARD CAST-FLAT NOSE)


As always, with Buffalo Bore Ammunition, we use real world firearms to give real world data and results. Laboratory test barrels tell you little about what kind of speed you can expect from your stock firearm.

All our 45 ACP+P loads utilize flash suppressed powders so that you will not be blinded by your own gunfire should you need to fire in the dark when the criminal element is at work.


The three JHP loads are design for defense against humans, while the two non-expanding loads are designed to shoot through large shoulder bones or the skull on a black bear. These non-expanding bullets also work well if you need to shoot through cover like car doors or stick frame walls.

title: For Sale:  1943 Mosin Nagant PU Sniper LOWERED price
postcontent:
I have a Mosin Nagant PU scoped Soviet sniper rifle. The rifle in an I.O. INC imported rifle. The reason I own it is due to the bore, which is mirror bright and strong rifling. Essentially, the bore was very well taken care of, including the crown. This rifle, besides being a historical piece, is quite a shooter. Using PPU heavy ball ammo, this rifle easily achieves 1 MOA accuracy, with most groups closer to 3/4 MOA.  The stock was the only ding on the rifle, with the original finish chipping off, so I refinished the rifle into an original look. The scope is not currently sighted in, however prior to refinishing the stock the scope was sighted in.

Some history on this particular piece as I have gotten from some research. This is a 1943 Ishevsk produced rifle. Serial number is KKxx meaning just two digits. It is a factory refurbed rifle with a strike/stamp number on the magazine floorplate. The bolt is not matching unfortunately. In correct form the scope's serial number is stamped into the left side of the receiver just above the woodline of the stock, and it matches the scope. The scope itself is original refurbished. It was refurbished in the Saranska Optics Plant in 1953. Saranska removed the previous markings of the original manufacture, which I believe to be from the Progress plant in 1943. The scope number is original to the rifle, just at refurb the old number was restamped onto the scope. Additionally the scope mount is original Izhevsh production sniper, un serialized original as common at that stage in the war, but there is a visable Izhevsk stamp on it. Later in refurbishment the rifle serial number was electropenciled onto the scope mount, which was common in the refurbishment process.

Essentially, through my research I have uncovered that the rifle is original Soviet sniper rifle that had undergone refurbishment post war, 1953. All the pieces are ORIGINAL, but refurbished.

I have no desire to ship the rifle as frankly I do not want to undergo the process.

And finally, the rifle is available if this is VISABLE, asking me if the rifle is still available will annoy the heck out of me. Any questions, trades, or picture requests feel free to ask.


The gun I want to buy is on sale. 500 is my bottom.

postcontent:
2011 Improved Outer Tactical Vest (IOTV)
Body Armor Vest 
GEN II, MultiCam, Includes Inserts
Size Large

Tactical Assault Panel TAP OCP Multicam Chest Rig

The U.S. Army began fielding the new second generation Improved Outer Tactical Vest (IOTV)
“The latest design Gen-II IOTV vest includes 17 improvements over the Gen-I vest. The new IOTV is designed with more versatile, modular approach, allowing units to configure their gear to better confront multiple threat levels in their unique environment” said Major Craig Fournier from PEO Soldier.

Improvements include a totally redesigned and removable yoke and collar, reversible and detachable side carriers and universal side pouch, and equipment anchor points on the front and rear which interface with items such as hydration systems and the Tactical Assault Panel or (TAP). In addition, the new design has better adjustability in the shoulders and hips, to better fit all sizes. The newly designed location for the side-plate is also adjustable to the wearer. Given the enhanced flexibility and modularity of the new kit, soldiers will be able to wear a more comfortable vest, and carry just the equipment they need for a mission. When required or possible, they could strip the IOTV down to its basic function, becoming a light weight load carrying vest, retaining effective protection, maneuverability and flexibility.

Features and Benefits:
More than three pounds lighter than OTV
Single-stage quick release added to the front of the vest allows a Soldier to doff the IOTV and its attachments with one pull
Other features include front and back pockets for SAPI, E-SAPI or other compatible hard armor plates and side adjustment straps. (Hard Plates not included)

Tactical Assault Panel TAP OCP Multicam Chest Rig 
MOLLE II Modular Lightweight Load-carrying Equipment II Tactical Assault Panel (TAP),  replaces the Fighting Load Carrier to allow for quick-release of equipment in emergency situations. TAP is compatible with the quick release system of the IOTV/SPCS. TAP can also be worn like a Ranger Assault Carrying Kit (RACK) using the external webbing harness. The Tactical Assault Panel (TAP) is designed to carry a variety of basic Modular Lightweight Load Carrying Equipment (MOLLE) pockets and pouches. The TAP is a replacement for the Fighting Load Carrier Vest and maintains the quick-release function of popular vests. Fully compatible with the Improved Outer Tactical Vest and Releasable Body Armor Vest, the TAP can be easily connected to and detached from the vest, allowing Soldiers to remove the heavy load when only body armor is needed.

title: For Sale:  Marlin 980 DL Bolt Action .22 Magnum WMR w/Redfield Widefield 2-7
postcontent: Up for sale is my Marlin 980 DL, chambered in .22 Magnum.  Manufactured in 1965. No serial number (not required back then).  Comes with three 7 round box magazines.  No rust or pitting.
